{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-project-js","path":"/projects/wolfswood-companion","webpackCompilationHash":"6efe87948671d91bc477","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"siteUrl":"https://sacha.me"}},"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>I've been interested in native application development for a long time, especially on iOS since most of my devices are from that ecosystem.</p>\n<p>While playing Destiny's Iron Banner event I came up with the idea for this app, which fell into a uncovered category in the App Store. Admittedly, it is not a completely new idea as similar applications already exist on the web or on other platforms, but I set out to create something new with a focus on design.</p>\n<figure>\n  <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 1100px;\">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 65.60906515580737%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" alt=\"shaders\" title=\"shaders\" src=\"/static/5721db18dec8c718b992217f6c0efea0/566ce/shaders.png\" srcset=\"/static/5721db18dec8c718b992217f6c0efea0/90c99/shaders.png 275w,\n/static/5721db18dec8c718b992217f6c0efea0/2cf63/shaders.png 550w,\n/static/5721db18dec8c718b992217f6c0efea0/566ce/shaders.png 1100w,\n/static/5721db18dec8c718b992217f6c0efea0/574ac/shaders.png 1650w,\n/static/5721db18dec8c718b992217f6c0efea0/cc414/shaders.png 1765w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1100px) 100vw, 1100px\" loading=\"lazy\">\n    </span>\n  <figcaption data-marginalia=\"right\">A selection of shaders, custom themes resembling Destiny-related subjects, which are available as <abbr title=\"In App Purchase\">IAP</abbr> inside the application.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p>From the beginning I wanted to create something that fit right into the iOS ecosystem, while still resembling the interface of Destiny. This meant thoroughly studying iOS interface guidelines and playing quite a bit of Destiny.</p>\n<h1 id=\"things-ive-learned\"><a href=\"#things-ive-learned\" aria-hidden class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Things I've learned</h1>\n<p>This was an entirely new experience for me, developing a native application for the first time, so of course there was a lot I had to learn.</p>\n<p>Getting into iOS development seems like an overwhelming task at the beginning, but there are lots of great tutorials and guides on the internet. I picked up pieces of information all around and tied them together to create a first working prototype, covering just the absolutely essential functionality. From there on I kept learning new things, using new frameworks, and including more and more functionality.</p>\n<figure>\n  <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 1100px;\">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 51.87927107061503%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/png;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\" alt=\"interface\" title=\"interface\" src=\"/static/040bca2bd551854ce42a2ff10bde8f58/566ce/interface.png\" srcset=\"/static/040bca2bd551854ce42a2ff10bde8f58/90c99/interface.png 275w,\n/static/040bca2bd551854ce42a2ff10bde8f58/2cf63/interface.png 550w,\n/static/040bca2bd551854ce42a2ff10bde8f58/566ce/interface.png 1100w,\n/static/040bca2bd551854ce42a2ff10bde8f58/574ac/interface.png 1650w,\n/static/040bca2bd551854ce42a2ff10bde8f58/1ebe0/interface.png 1756w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1100px) 100vw, 1100px\" loading=\"lazy\">\n    </span>\n  <figcaption data-marginalia=\"right\">The application works regardless of platform, number of characters. Players can customise and make the application their own using various shaders.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p>I wanted to make the application available for free and to include additional shaders — custom themes I created resembling Destiny-related subjects — as In App Purchases. This lead to some more difficulties, mainly setting up the iTunes Connect account correctly. In the end, however, I managed to include everything I wanted in the app and officially release it.</p>\n<h1 id=\"technologies-ive-used\"><a href=\"#technologies-ive-used\" aria-hidden class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Technologies I've used</h1>\n<p>The application is written using only Swift code, which I found a lot easier to understand than the traditional Objective-C code that was used up until recently. Swift was a great language to learn and write and I look forward to creating more applications in Swift.</p>\n<p>Aside from the language I've used many features of Cocoa and UIKit, and of course StoreKit for the In App Purchase functionality.</p>","frontmatter":{"date":"01 April 2016","path":"/projects/wolfswood-companion","title":"Wolfswood Companion","end":2016,"client":null,"link":"https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/wolfswood-companion/id1091989511?ls=1&mt=8","repo":null,"team":1,"pattern":"checker","background":"rgb(40, 45, 49)","teaser":"Wolfswood Companion is a planning utility for the console game Destiny. It helps players with planning the monthly Iron Banner event and achieving the maximum level in order to obtain all the rewards.","tags":["Mobile","App","Swift"],"technologies":["Swift","Cocoa","StoreKit"],"tasks":["Native App Development","Design","App Publishing","Marketing"],"hero":{"childImageSharp":{"sizes":{"aspectRatio":1.5241796200345423,"src":"/static/d288f23805b370c2b34a90840d882b68/95331/hero.png","srcSet":"/static/d288f23805b370c2b34a90840d882b68/51ac9/hero.png 275w,\n/static/d288f23805b370c2b34a90840d882b68/7cff2/hero.png 550w,\n/static/d288f23805b370c2b34a90840d882b68/95331/hero.png 1100w,\n/static/d288f23805b370c2b34a90840d882b68/0ec6e/hero.png 1650w,\n/static/d288f23805b370c2b34a90840d882b68/cd4e7/hero.png 1765w","sizes":"(max-width: 1100px) 100vw, 1100px"}}}}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false}}}